## Economic Impact

The abolition of slavery had profound economic consequences. The Southern economy, heavily dependent on slave labor, faced disruption. Many farmers who could no longer rely on enslaved labor had to sell land or adjust their business models ([Askinglot, 2020](https://askinglot.com/what-was-the-impact-of-the-13th-amendment)).

For freed African Americans, the transition to paid labor was fraught with challenges. Racial discrimination severely limited job opportunities, especially in the South, where hatred and segregation persisted ([Askinglot, 2020](https://askinglot.com/what-was-the-impact-of-the-13th-amendment)).

| Economic Impact Aspect          | Description                                                                                  |
|--------------------------------|----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------|
| Disruption of Southern Economy | Loss of slave labor forced restructuring and land sales                                    |
| Employment Opportunities        | Opened for some, but racial discrimination limited access for African Americans             |
| Labor Contracts and Black Codes| Many freedmen forced into exploitative labor contracts under threat of legal penalties      |
| Long-Term Economic Inequality   | African Americans remained in low-paying jobs with limited land ownership                   |

